een mind and body. It represents the very engine of life.\r\n\r\nNow, heart health is intimately intertwined with mental and emotional health. Therefore emotional stress can significantly affect the heart. You almost gave me a heart attack! Can emotional stress really cause heart attacks or even worse, lead to death? Researchers from the Psychophysiological Investigations of Myocardial Ischemia (PIMI) study set out to examine that very question. Mental stress has long been associated with coronary heart disease (CHD) and its complications. Their research has demonstrated a greater than two-fold increase in subsequent cardiac events, such as heart attack, in those who suffer from heart dysfunction in the setting of mental\r\n\r\nChronic mental stress characterized by depression, lack of social support, or hostility have all been tied to an increased rate of heart disease.\r\n\r\nHeart disease comes in many forms and is the number one cause of death in the United States. The most common cause of heart disease is coronary artery disease (the narrowing or blockage of the coronary arteries, the blood vessels that supply blood to the heart). Chronic stress and anxiety can often have cardiovascular symptoms such as increased heart rate, palpations and increased blood pressure. It is extremely important to minimize the effect of stress on your heart over time.\r\n\r\nA possible solution\r\n\r\nUnhealthy lifestyles increase the burden of coronary heart disease. In addition to hypertension, dyslipidemia, and diabetes, physical inactivity, obesity, smoking, and consuming an unhealthy diet are also significant risk factors for CHD. Lifestyle modification is an essential population-based strategy for the prevention of CHD through risk factor reduction. In particular, lifestyle interventions have been shown to reduce blood pressure in pre-hypertensive and hypertensive individuals.\r\n\r\nAt the Carolina Partners Wellness center we offer a collaborative, holistic approach to heart health. With alternative stress management techniques, and whole body nutritional support, our goal is to help your body deal with physiological and mental stress more efficiently. This way, the impact of stress on your heart may be reduced.\r\n\r\n9 Best Foods for your Heart:\r\n\r\nOatmeal  Full of omega  3 fatty acids, folate, and potassium. It is rich in fiber has the ability to reduce levels of LDL (bad) cholesterol and aid in keeping arteries clear.\r\n\r\nSalmon  Immensely rich in Omega-3 fatty acids. Salmon can reduce blood pressure and minimize blood clots. 2-3 servings per weeks may reduce your risk of dying of a heart attack by up to 1/3. Other fish like salmon are mackerel, tuna, herring and sardines will also boost your heart health.\r\n\r\nAvocado  Packed with monounsaturated fat, and can help lower LDL while raising HDL.\r\n\r\nWalnuts  High in Omega 3 fatty acids walnuts are a heart-healthy snack.\r\n\r\nBerries  Blueberries, raspberries, and strawberries are full of anti-inflammatories, which aid in reducing your risk of heart disease and cancer.\r\n\r\nLegumes  Lentils, chickpeas, and black and kidney beans are packed with omega-3 fatty acids, calcium, and soluble fiber.\r\n\r\nSpinach  Is said to keep your heart in tip-top shape. Its full of lutein, folate, potassium and fiber.\r\n\r\n[Flaxseed](http://66.228.62.131/products/flaxseed-oil-1250-mg-120-gels \"\")  Full of fiber and omega-3 and omega- 6 fatty acids.\r\n\r\nOlive Oil Full of monounsaturated fats, it can lower the LDL cholesterol and reduce the risk of developing heart disease.\r\n',NULL,1,'2012-05-17 16:58:55','2012-05-21 17:17:16',1),(24,'Spring Time! Detox Time!','spring-time-detox-time',NULL,'2012-03-01 00:00:00','Spring is typically the time of year that most people think about detoxing. The weather is better and everyone is looking forward to those lazy summer days.\r\n\r\nBut what is detoxification anyway?\r\n\r\nFor many, detoxification conjures up unpleasant images of colon cleansing and self-inflicted discomfort for a few hours. This is usually done by taking laxatives and fiber among other things. But what does that really accomplish? A few days later everything is back to the way it was.what a waste? (no pun intended!)\r\n\r\nWhen I talk about detox, I refer to the process where the natural cleansing organs of the body are gently supported through good nutrition and perhaps specific natural herbs. It should be a process that takes place daily. But for a focused, purposeful time of detoxification, the mind body and spirit should all be cleansed over a period of about 1  4 weeks. I use whole foods primarily to detoxify the primary organs of elimination, the liver, kidney, lungs, skin and large intestines. Detoxification is a whole body process and while colon detoxification is important, when the rest of the body is ignored, detoxing the colon is generally no very effective.\r\n\r\nHow do you know if you need to Detox?\r\n\r\nIf you answer yes to any of the following questions, a structured detox program is right for you.\r\n\r\nHave you gone more than 6 months without participating in a structured detoxification program that takes place over 7 or more days?\r\n\r\nDo you experience any of the following: fatigue, headaches, constipation, bad breath, mood swings, menstrual problems, low libido, skin issues, erectile dysfunction, difficulty losing weight, or food cravings?\r\n\r\nNow, any good detox program places food at the forefront. Supplements, powders and other detoxification aids only work well if the foods been eaten support detoxification and they themselves dont contain toxins.\r\n\r\nPlease note: it is best to do a detox program that is supervised by a qualified professional. People who are chronically ill, or taking multiple medications should not participate in most detoxification programs unless cleared by their physician.\r\n\r\nAs I always say, lets take out the garbage!\r\n\r\n-Dr. Parkes',NULL,1,'2012-05-21 19:04:48','2012-05-21 19:05:42',1),(25,'Alternative Treatments for Anxiety and Depression','alternative-treatments-for-anxiety-and-depression',NULL,'2012-05-01 00:00:00','May is Mental Health Awareness month. Did you know that 1 in 4 adults struggle with a treatable mental health condition each year? Thats almost 60 million people! Do you know a family member, friend, or colleague quietly struggling with depression, anxiety, posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD), substance abuse, or other mental health issue?  Two of the most commonly treated mental health disorders are anxiety disorders and depressive disorders.\r\n \r\n**Anxiety** \r\nAnxiety disorders are among the most common mental illnesses in America; more than 40 million people are affected by these debilitating illnesses each year. Most people experience feelings of anxiety before an important event such as a big exam, business presentation or first date. Anxiety disorders, however, are illnesses that cause people to feel uneasy, frightened, and/or distressed very easily, often for no apparent reason. Many people suffering from anxiety disorders also experience heart palpitations, shortness of breath and chest pain. Left untreated, these disorders can dramatically reduce productivity and significantly diminish an individuals quality of life.  There are two types of anxiety disorders:\r\n\r\n**Panic Disorders:** are characterized by panic attacks, which are sudden feelings of terror that strike repeatedly and without warning.\r\n\r\nPhysical symptoms include chest pain, heart palpitations, and shortness of breath, dizziness and abdominal discomfort. \r\n\r\n**Generalized Anxiety Disorders:** are characterized by chronic, exaggerated worry about everyday routine, like life events and activities lasting at least six months.  In this case, the person is almost always anticipating the worst even though there is little reason to expect it.\r\nIt is often accompanied by physical symptoms, such as fatigue, trembling, muscle tension, headache, or nausea. \r\n\r\n**Depression** \r\nFeeling sad, or what we may call \"depressed\", happens to all of us. The sensation usually passes after a while. However, a person with a depressive disorder - clinical depression - finds that this state interferes with their daily life. Their normal functioning is undermined to such an extent the individual and those close to them are affected by it. There are several forms of depression (depressive disorders): major depressive disorder, dysthymic disorder, postpartum depression, psychotic depression, bipolar depression and seasonal affective disorder (SAD) are the main types of depression that are seen clinically.  Common symptoms of depression include: A constant feeling of sadness, anxiety, and emptiness, hopelessness, memory and concentration problems, insomnia, low libido or Fatigue.\r\n\r\n**What Causes Anxiety and Depressive Disorders?**\r\nThe causes of these disorders are many. They can be different for each person and range from a traumatic life experience, food sensitivities, vitamin or mineral deficiencies, environmental toxicities to an inherited genetic defect in a biochemical pathway.  Also, more than one factor can be present depending on the individual. \r\n\r\n**What Are the Alternative Treatments for Anxiety and Depressive Disorders?**\r\nStandard medical treatments and therapy work well for these disorders.  Specific medications can help improve mood, decrease anxiety symptoms and improve the overall quality of life.  However, most people would greatly benefit from alternative and natural treatments which can provide even greater improvement in conjunction with their medication.  Natural therapies are aimed at correcting the underlying cause of the depressive or anxiety symptoms and could decrease the need for prescription medication over time. Also there are usually no side effects associated with natural therapies.  At the Carolina Partners Wellness Center, we provide a comprehensive, holistic approach to treating these disorders with lifestyle modifications, nutrition, herbs and whole food supplements.  Special care is taken to investigate the possible underlying cause of the disorder and each patient is given an individualized protocol to help improve their condition.\r\n\r\n**Schedule a free phone consultation: 919.792.3940 to find out what Dr. Parkes can do for you!**\r\n\r\n**Stress Relief Tips:**\r\n\r\n- Remind yourself that life is not a fire-drill\r\n\r\n- Give yourself more time. Time will help lower your stress\r\n\r\n- Prioritize, by asking yourself what matters  in the long run\r\n\r\n- Look for the lesson that you can learn from every problem\r\n\r\n- Eat right\r\n\r\n- Set realistic goals\r\n\r\n- Reduce the urge to be \"perfect\"\r\n\r\n- Manage your anger\r\n\r\n- Push away negativity of any kind\r\n\r\n- Sleep\r\n\r\n- Stay Fit\r\n\r\n- Eat Healthy\r\n\r\n- Manage Time\r\n\r\n- Relax\r\n\r\n- Take a Break\r\n\r\n- Seek Balance\r\n\r\n- Socialize\r\n\r\n- Laugh often\r\n',NULL,1,'2012-05-21 19:13:52','2012-05-21 19:47:49',1),(26,'MOVE IT!','move-it',NULL,'2012-04-03 00:00:00','Physical activity is essential to health.  Did you know that there are approximately 206 bones, 639 skeletal muscles and 360 joints in the human body?  These all have one major function. Movement! Frequent exercise is a necessary ingredient for your body to function well.  Exercise is just as important as sleep, food and water.  Without adequate exercise the body will not function well.  The result may be pain, chronic diseases or even loss of mobility. \r\nHere are a few key things that physical exercise can help with.\r\n\r\n**Control Your Weight**\r\nBoth diet and physical activity play a critical role in controlling your weight. You gain weight when the calories you burn, including those burned during physical activity, are less than the calories you eat or drink.  Work your way up to 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic exercise per week.\r\n\r\n**Reduce Your Risk of Cardiovascular Disease**\r\nHeart disease and stroke are two of the leading causes of death in the United States. But following the Guidelines and getting at least 150 minutes a week (2 hours and 30 minutes) of moderate-intensity aerobic activity can put you at a lower risk for these diseases. You can reduce your risk even further with more physical activity. Regular physical activity can also lower your blood pressure and improve your cholesterol levels. \r\n\r\n**Reduce your risk of Type 2 Diabetes and Metabolic Syndrome**\r\nRegular physical activity can reduce your risk of developing type 2 diabetes and metabolic syndrome. Metabolic syndrome is a condition in which you have some combination of too much fat around the waist, high blood pressure, low HDL cholesterol, high triglycerides, or high blood sugar. Research shows that lower rates of these conditions are seen with 120 to 150 minutes (2 hours to 2 hours and 30 minutes) a week of at least moderate-intensity aerobic activity. And the more physical activity you do, the lower your risk will be. Already have type 2 diabetes? Regular physical activity can help control your blood glucose levels. \r\n\r\n**Reduce Your Risk of Some Cancers** \r\nBeing physically active lowers your risk for two types of cancer: colon and breast. Research shows that:\r\nPhysically active people have a lower risk of colon cancer than do people who are not active.  Physically active women have a lower risk of breast cancer than do people who are not active.\r\n\r\n**Improve Your Mental Health and Mood**\r\nRegular physical activity can help keep your thinking, learning, and judgment skills sharp as you age. It can also reduce your risk of depression and may help you sleep better. Research has shown that doing aerobic or a mix of aerobic and muscle-strengthening activities 3 to 5 times a week for 30 to 60 minutes can help give you these mental health benefits. \r\n\r\n**5 Healthy Fitness Tips**   \r\n       \r\n- Lift weights and your spirits - Studies show that even a little bit of exercise can affect mood-controlling in your brain. \r\n\r\n- Mix it up - Missed your daily workout? DO strength training during commercial breaks of your favorite tv show. Lunges, squats, and crunches.\r\n\r\n- Change your scenery - Ditch the treadmill for some new terrain and explore a new path in your neighborhood. \r\n\r\n- Take a Class - The fact that you pay for it will push you to get your moneys worth and the energy from others will boost your own. \r\n\r\n- Buddy up - Working out with a friend is a great way to stick with a fitness routine. \r\n',NULL,1,'2012-05-21 19:42:25','2012-05-21 19:46:00',1),(27,'Let\'s Eat! Recipe for Creamed Kale over Rice','let-s-eat-recipe-for-creamed-kale-over-rice',NULL,'2012-04-16 00:00:00','Serves: 4  Preparation Time: 30 minutes \r\n\r\n**Ingredients:** \r\n\r\n- 2 bunches kale, tough stems and center ribs removed and leaves coarsely chopped\r\n\r\n- 2 cups shiitake mushrooms, sliced\r\n\r\n- 1 medium onion, chopped\r\n\r\n- 2 cups frozen peas\r\n\r\n- 3/4 cup raw cashews\r\n\r\n- 3/4 cup unsweetened almond milk\r\n\r\n- 2 cups cooked wild, brown or white rice\r\n\r\n\r\n**Instructions:**\r\nIn a large covered skillet, water saut the kale, mushrooms, onion, and peas  over  medium heat, until kale is tender, about 10 minutes. Stir occasionally and add water as needed. \r\nMeanwhile, blend the cashews, milk and onion flakes in a food processor or high powered blender until smooth and creamy. \r\nStir cashew cream sauce into kale mixture.\r\n\r\nServe over cooked rice.\r\n',NULL,1,'2012-05-21 19:50:09','2012-05-21 19:52:55',1),(28,'Nutrition vs. Technology','nutrition-vs-technology',NULL,'2012-03-23 00:00:00','The month of March is known as National Nutrition Month so it is only fitting that we talk about isolated and synthetic vs. whole food nutrients. Vitamins and mineral supplements have generally had a healthy reputation in regards to our diet. \r\nHowever, in past centuries, people were able to stay healthy without supplements because they generally ate a healthier diet than we do today and therefore, less prone to the degenerative diseases.  Today we are faced with increasing amounts of heart disease, diabetes, arthritis and cancer. It is now becoming increasingly difficult to stay healthy without supplements.  If we take this a step further we can also notice that in the past, foods were grown on small farms in mineral-rich soils. However, today, foods are grown in mineral-deficient soils on factory farms where the main goal is to produce high quantity rather than high quality food. Over the years modern technology has advanced immensely so that we can now isolate the vitamins and minerals our modern day diets are lacking. The question now is, Is this sufficient to promote optimum health and is this an improvement on what our ancestors did? History tells us that when European travelers were crossing the Atlantic Ocean in route to the New World they discovered if they drank fresh lime-juice they did not get scurvy (a Vitamin C deficiency resulting in bleeding gums, weakness and joint pain ect). It wasnt until the 20th century that scientists finally isolated the beneficial component in citrus fruits as Vitamin C. What we fail to realize is by taking isolated Vitamin C in the form of ascorbic acid, its only a temporary fix. As soon as the ascorbic acid is discontinued, the symptoms and disease return. On the other hand, if one takes Vitamin C made from an extract of whole green peppers, not only do the symptoms disappear but the scurvy is gone when discontinued.\r\n\r\nAlthough technology has been very beneficial in helping us understand the way food and nutrients work, we can now see that isolating and concentrating single nutrients does not have the same effect as using the whole food.  When selecting vitamins and supplements, be sure to read the label and look for whole food ingredients. If no foods are listed, then that product may be isolated chemicals and may not provide you with any health benefits. In fact, synthetic vitamin products may actually be harmful and cause health issues in the long run. Eating a diet rich in real, unprocessed whole foods is the best way to ensure you are getting proper nutrition.  Added to that, supplementing natural whole food vitamins and minerals can enhance overall nutritional status. \r\n\r\nIn our practice, we utilize whole food organic supplements made by Standard Process, inc. We emphasize a diet rich in whole foods and help patients to return to a more natural way of eating.  For more information, feel free to give us a call and schedule a free consultation.\r\n',NULL,1,'2012-05-21 20:02:25','2012-05-21 20:02:25',1),(29,'Omega 3 Fatty acids and Mental Health','omega-3-fatty-acids-and-mental-health',NULL,'2012-05-10 00:00:00','Omega-3 fatty acids are considered essential fatty acids: They are necessary for human health but the body cant make them -- you have to get them through food. Omega-3 fatty acids can be found in fish, such as salmon, tuna, and halibut, other seafood including algae and krill, some plants, and nut oils. Also known as polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs), omega-3 fatty acids play a crucial role in brain function.  Omega-3 fatty acids are highly concentrated in the brain and appear to be important for cognitive (brain memory and performance) and behavioral function. Symptoms of omega-3 fatty acid deficiency include fatigue, poor memory, dry skin, heart problems, mood swings or depression, and poor circulation.\r\n\r\nUses in Mental Health\r\n\r\n**Depression** \r\nSeveral studies have found that people who took omega-3 fatty acids in addition to prescription antidepressants had a greater improvement in symptoms than those who took antidepressants alone. Other studies show that omega-3 fatty acid intake helps protect against postpartum depression, among other benefits.\r\n\r\n**Cognitive Decline**\r\nA number of studies show that reduced intake of omega-3 fatty acids is associated with increased risk of age related cognitive decline or dementia, including Alzheimer\'s disease. \r\n\r\n**ADHD**\r\nChildren with attention deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) may have low levels of certain essential fatty acids (including EPA and DHA). In a clinical study of nearly 100 boys, those with lower levels of omega-3 fatty acids had more learning and behavioral problems (such as temper tantrums and sleep disturbances) than boys with normal omega-3 fatty acid levels.\r\n\r\n**Anxiety**\r\nThe results of a 2011 study from the National Institutes of Health suggest that increased intakes of omega 3 fatty acids could be beneficial for young, healthy people by reducing anxiety symptoms and inflammation, a process that plays a role in many diseases.\r\n\r\nConsumers should be aware that not all Omega 3 fish oil supplements are created equal.  The purity and concentration of supplements vary widely depending on the source of the fish and the processes used to create the fish oil.  Inexpensive, bargain brands have been shown to contain dangerous chemicals and heavy metals such as mercury.  If you are considering taking omega 3 fish oils, talk to your health care provider or schedule a supplement consultation at the wellness center.  \r\nWe carry both liquid and gel caps at the wellness center and we only use physician grade supplements that are high quality and highly purified.  You may also shop online at our trusted site www.goldensealwellness.com.\r\n\r\nSources: The National Institute of Health ( nih.gov), University of Maryland Center for Integrative Medicine (umm.edu)\r\n\r\n\r\n',NULL,1,'2012-05-21 20:18:39','2012-05-21 20:18:39',1),(30,'Lets talk about MILK!','lets-talk-about-milk',NULL,'2012-06-05 01:01:00','![](https://www.goldensealwellness.com/spree/uploads/505/original/milk.jpg \"\")\r\n\r\nAt least once or twice a week, I am invariably faced with the question, Where will I get my calcium if I dont drink milk?\r\n\r\nPersonally, I grew up on milk like many other people. At school milk was free as a snack or with lunch. At home my grandmother told me milk would make my teeth and bones strong. On television, there were many commercials with happy cows, laughing children, successful athletes and trusted healthcare professionals, all touting the wonders of milk. It was engraved in my mind at an early age that milk/dairy was an essential part of a healthy diet. In fact, this is the belief that most people are raised with and they pass it on to their children. In fact, most food pyramids still recommend that we eat 3 servings of dairy per day.\r\n\r\nThe truth is, humans were not made to digest cow milk. Young children may tolerate small amounts better than adults, however, nobody should be consuming dairy products on a regular basis.\r\n\r\nThis is why:\r\n\r\n- Milk/Cow Dairy; organic, fat free, 1%, 2%, low fat, raw or any other variety promotes inflamation within the body.\r\n- Inflamation creates an internal environment that supports variety of diseases such as heart disease, diabetes, cancer, asthma, eczema, thyroid irregularities, allergies, colitis, autoimmune conditions, fibromyalgia and many others.\r\n- Milk today is not the same as it was 50 or 100 years ago. Nowadays, cows raised commercially for their milk are subjected to specialized feedings, growth hormones and antibiotics in improve productivity and minimize loss.\r\n- The toxins/drugs/hormones that the cows are exposed to are found in measurable quantities in their milk. (This makes sense! It is the same reason why nursing mothers shouldnt drink alcohol or take certain drugs it all comes out in the milk!)\r\n- Cheese, ice cream and butter have significantly concentrated amounts of milk. In fact, hard cheeses have 10 times more milk than the same weight of milk.\r\n- All milk contains a hormone called inuslin-like growth factor (IGF-1). This hormone causes cells to divide and grow rapidly. Good news for the baby calves who grow into enormous cows in a relatively short amount of time! Bad news for humans who are watching their waistlines. Even worse news for humans when it comes to cancer risk because, IGF-1 causes all cells, including cancer cells to grow more rapidly.\r\n- Infants and young children often have allergies to milk and dairy that shows up as asthma, eczema, colic, and a variety of digestive complaints.\r\n- Contrary to popular belief, milk is over 80% water and therefore not a high protein source. In fact, most of the protein in milk is casein, a very allergenic protein.\r\n- Another popular question I get is What about yogurt? Yogurt is dairy, partially digested by bacteria so, it doesnt have as many harsh effects on the digestive system, however, I still dont recommend it.\r\n- Lactose, the sugar in milk is not well tolerated by most adults. People of Latin American and African decent have a particularly hard time digesting lactose. This causes many digestive disturbances like gas, bloating, diarrhea or constipation.\r\n- And, finally, the calcium issue. Milk does contain calcium. However, in order for calcium to be properly absorbed and utilized by the body, there needs to be magnesium and vitamin D to go along with it. The fact is, populations that consume high amounts of dairy have higher rates of osteoporosis. Green leafy vegetables actually have a balanced amount of calcium, magnesium and other minerals that are better absorbed and utilized by the body than the calcium in milk. Therefore, my top picks for high calcium foods are spinach, turnip greens, mustard greens, collard greens, kale, romaine lettuce and broccoli. Having a diet that is very low in dairy products and high in green leafy vegetables is the best way to protect against osteoporosis and increase dietary calcium. There are many calcium supplements on the market, but the truth is, many of them are not absorbable and are therefore a waste of money. So to be safe, I always follow my personal motto: Food First!\r\n\r\nHeres the bottom line: It is okay to enjoy ice cream, cheeses, creamy sauces, yogurts and a range of other dairy products from time to time. Lets face it, they taste really good! However, these toxic foods should be occasional treats and by no means a regular part of the diet. They do not promote good health. My picks for substituting milk are almond milk (Blue Diamond brand), rice milk and of course, my new favorite  dairy free coconut milk ice cream!\r\n\r\n-Dr. Parkes\r\n',NULL,1,'2012-06-05 01:02:30','2012-06-05 01:07:06',1),(31,'Weight Loss vs. Fat Loss','weight-loss-vs-fat-loss',NULL,'2012-06-12 00:00:00','![](https://goldensealwellness.com/spree/uploads/561/original/weight-loss.jpg?1342477989 \"\")\r\n\r\nHaving a healthy body weight goes far beyond the number on the scale.  Two people who weigh the same may look very different based on the percentage of muscle, fat and abdominal fat that they have.  The body composition analysis test measures the relative percentages of muscle and fat and can predict whether your weight is healthy or not.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that when starting a weight loss program, you should make sure that there is a focus on fat loss primarily instead of just overall weight loss.  Many weight loss programs can cause participants to lose water, muscle, fat and even bone mass which can sometimes be translated to large amounts of weight being lost, but with very small amounts of that being fat. \r\n \r\nOf all the places to store fat on the body, abdominal fat presents the greatest health risks. Generally speaking, abdominal fat is either visceral (surrounding the abdominal organs) or subcutaneous (lying between the skin and the abdominal wall). Fat accumulated in the lower body (the pear shape) is subcutaneous, while fat in the abdominal area (the apple shape) is largely visceral.  Theres also evidence that waist circumference is a better predictor of health problems than the popular body mass index (BMI), which indicates only total body fat. The good news here is that visceral fat yields fairly easily to diet and exercise with benefits ranging from lower blood pressure to more favorable cholesterol levels.\r\n\r\n![](https://www.goldensealwellness.com/spree/uploads/553/original/fat.jpg?1342476781 \"\")\r\n\r\nOne reason excess visceral fat is so harmful could be its location near the portal vein, which carries blood from the intestinal area to the liver. Substances released by visceral fat, including free fatty acids, enter the portal vein and travel to the liver, where they can influence the production of blood lipids. Visceral fat is directly linked with higher total cholesterol and LDL (bad) cholesterol, lower HDL (good) cholesterol, and insulin resistance.\r\n \r\n![](https://www.goldensealwellness.com/spree/uploads/558/original/exercise.png?1342477003 \"\")\r\n\r\nThe starting point for bringing weight under control, in general, and combating abdominal fat, in particular, is regular moderate-intensity physical activity  at least 30 minutes per day (and perhaps up to 60 minutes per day) to control weight.\r\n\r\nAlong with intense physical activity, strength training may help fight abdominal fat.  A University of Pennsylvania study followed obese women, ages 24-44 years of age for two years. Compared to participants who received only advice about exercise, those given an hour of weight training twice a week reduced their proportion of body fat by nearly 4%  and were more successful in keeping off visceral fat. Lastly, diet is vital. \r\n\r\nPay attention to portion size, and emphasize complex carbohydrates such as fruits, veggies, whole grains, and lean proteins vs. simple carbohydrates like white bread, refined-grain pasta, and sugary drinks. Replacing saturated fats and trans-fat with polyunsaturated fats can also help. Something to keep in mind is that you are not drastically cutting calories. This will cause your body to go into starvation mode, which will slow your metabolism down and cause it to store fat less efficiently later on.  To get started on a fat loss program and learn how to keep it off for life,  call us and schedule an appointment today.  We can measure your visceral and get you started on a path to a healthier body. Consultations are free. \r\n\r\n919.792.3940\r\n\r\n![](https://goldensealwellness.com/spree/uploads/554/original/tips.png?1342476798 \"\")\r\n\r\n![](https://goldensealwellness.com/spree/uploads/555/original/weightloss.png?1342476809 \"\")\r\n',NULL,1,'2012-07-16 22:03:59','2012-07-18 14:53:34',1),(32,'Raising Healthy Kids','raising-healthy-kids',NULL,'2012-07-17 21:24:00','![](https://www.goldensealwellness.com/spree/uploads/563/original/healthy.jpg?1342560862 \"\")\r\n\r\nUnfortunately today, children are more unhealthy than their parents. For the first time in history, it is being projected that this generation of children will die before their parents. This is due to wide-spread chronic diseases such as cancer, obesity, diabetes, heart disease, mental illness and autoimmune disease that are now seen in children. Children are also more medicated now than ever before.\r\n\r\n**Why is this?**\r\nThe truth is, the parents have stopped being good role models and disciplinarians.  They are often uninvolved or playing the role of friend to their children instead of the role of parent. Since children copy the behavior of parents, busy lifestyles and lack of knowledge has led to a rampant over-consumption of fast/refined food and sugar among both adults and consequently children.  During the early stages of development through puberty, children need specific vitamins, minerals and other nutrients in order to grow and function properly.  The lack of this results in diseases like type 2 diabetes, hypertension, hormonal imbalances, behavioral problems and obesity that are traditionally mostly seen in the older population. Today, almost one in two children is either overweight or obese.  The number of obese children and adolescents has quadrupled in the past four decades. As a parent, you are the primary role model for your child. Your behaviors have a direct impact on your children. Healthy eating and physical activity are good lifestyle habits for the entire family.\r\n\r\nChildren who learn the value of exercise and the how-to of choosing healthy snacks and meals are more likely to continue such habits throughout their lives. As a parent, you should be involved in your childs life. Children of parents who generally know their childs whereabouts, set clear rules, and participate appropriately in their childs school and play activities are more likely to report healthy habitssuch as eating a healthy breakfast and lunch and consuming fruits and vegetables. These children also report high levels of family communication.\r\n\r\nIt is also important that as a parent, you get the facts on nutrition.  The market is flooded with unhealthy, appealing food choices and without the right information, it is easy for you to unintentionally feed your family in a way that negatively impacts their health. As a rule of thumb, it is always better to eat natural whole foods that are not packaged.  Foods that come with a nutrition label and multiple ingredients are generally a bad idea. Remove temptation like high calorie snack foods such as cookies and chips from the house. Instead, stock up on nutritious/healthy snacks, such as  nuts, fresh fruit and carrots. You can also have children participate in meal preparation as much as possible. Children are more likely to taste and eat foods that they help choose and prepare. Learning through participation also helps children feel like they are helping the family. Mealtime can be a highlight of your familys day by making it a time for conversation and fun, as well as food. No meal should last less than 15 minutes. The stomach needs about 20 minutes to get the message to the brain that it is satisfied.  Also, never use food as a punishment or reward. Withholding food can make children anxious that they will not get enough food, thus stimulating overeating. Similarly, using food as a reward teaches children that some foods are better or more valuable than others.   Finally, set aside time every week to schedule at least 1 or 2 family activities, such as hiking, biking, raking leaves, playing tag, gardening, or playing Frisbee.  This helps children see physical activity as fun instead of a task.  Since each child is unique, it is also important to get specific nutrition for their particular needs.  To get more information, set up a free phone consultation at our office.\r\n\r\n![](https://www.goldensealwellness.com/spree/uploads/562/original/1.png?1342560687 \"\")\r\n\r\n',NULL,1,'2012-07-17 21:31:11','2012-07-17 21:34:57',1);
